data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9 (.NET 9), the Cosmos DB provider began **throwing `InvalidOperationException` by default** for synchronous API calls, but offered a **sync-over-async opt-in** escape hatch (e.g., via `EnablePrimitiveCollections` / cosmos options configuration).

In **EF Core 11 (.NET 11), that opt-in is removed entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider will throw `InvalidOperationException` with **no workaround** — because the underlying Cosmos SDK v3 is async-only.

## The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` / `Task` instead of `T` / `void`
2. Replace `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
3. `await` each call; mark methods `async`
4. Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)

This is a **cascading change** — every caller up the chain must also become async, all the way to the controller actions (which should already return `Task<IActionResult>`).
